04079nam a22005535i 9780226673776DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20092006ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802266737767 a10.7208/97802266737762doi  a(DE-B1597)524990  a(OCoLC)1135563518  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 7aSOC0000002bisacsh1 aPolletta, Francesca, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aIt Was Like a Fever :bStorytelling in Protest and Politics /cFrancesca Polletta. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2009] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Why Stories Matter -- t2. “It was like a fever . . .”: Why People Protest -- t3. Strategy as Metonymy: Why Activists Choose the Strategies They Do -- t4. Stories and Reasons: Why Deliberation Is Only Sometimes Democratic -- t5. Ways of Knowing and Stories Worth Telling: Why Casting Oneself as a Victim Sometimes Hurts the Cause -- t6. Remembering Dr. King on the House and Senate Floor: Why Movements Have the Impacts They Do -- t7. Conclusion: Folk Wisdom and Scholarly Tales -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aActivists and politicians have long recognized the power of a good story to move people to action. In early 1960 four black college students sat down at a whites-only lunch counter in Greensboro, North Carolina, and refused to leave. Within a month sit-ins spread to thirty cities in seven states. Student participants told stories of impulsive, spontaneous action—this despite all the planning that had gone into the sit-ins. “It was like a fever,” they said. Francesca Polletta’s It Was Like a Fever sets out to account for the power of storytelling in mobilizing political and social movements. Drawing on cases ranging from sixteenth-century tax revolts to contemporary debates about the future of the World Trade Center site, Polletta argues that stories are politically effective not when they have clear moral messages, but when they have complex, often ambiguous ones. The openness of stories to interpretation has allowed disadvantaged groups, in particular, to gain a hearing for new needs and to forge surprising political alliances. But popular beliefs in America about storytelling as a genre have also hurt those challenging the status quo. A rich analysis of storytelling in courtrooms, newsrooms, public forums, and the United States Congress, It Was Like a Fever offers provocative new insights into the dynamics of culture and contention.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCommunication in folklore. 0aCommunicationxPolitical aspects. 0aPolitics and culture. 0aProtest movements. 0aSocial movements. 0aSocial sciencesxElectronic books. 0aSocial sciences. 0aStorytellingxPolitical aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311063538640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226673776423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226673776.jpg  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles